ng-bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39=
;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">A former Wall Streeter who did a stint in =
Washington described
the first two weeks of Trump II as =E2=80=9Ca giant blender=E2=80=9D of =E2=
=80=9Cfog and chaos=E2=80=9D stirred up to distract people from three of Tr=
ump=E2=80=99s near-term goals: getting his =E2=80=9Cidiot cabinet picks=E2=
=80=9D through the Senate; positioning <strong>Russ Vought</strong>, Trump=
=E2=80=99s pick to head the O.M.B., to =E2=80=9Ctake the shit out of the bu=
dget=E2=80=9D; and getting congressional approval for the extension of the =
about-to-expire Trump I tax cuts. And, he said, Wall Street is on board. =
=E2=80=9C[The tax cut extension] is what they really want,=E2=80=9D he
explained. =E2=80=9CUntil he can=E2=80=99t do that, they=E2=80=99re perfect=
ly happy to back him and focus on the things that warm their hearts, like s=
hutting USAID. But if this goes on too long and/or the stock market goes do=
wn, they=E2=80=99re not going to be so pleased.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"mar=
gin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;=
">Another veteran Wall Street banker, who worked for Trump back in the day =
and knows him well, offered a more nuanced assessment of the tariff situati=
on, as well as the
view from the upper echelons of Wall Street, which has been conspicuously s=
ilent. There are two types of people who work for Trump in Washington, he t=
old me=E2=80=94=E2=80=9Cthose who love tariffs, and those who are afraid to=
 tell him the truth.=E2=80=9D He said he has no idea what Trump =E2=80=9Cis=
 trying to solve for,=E2=80=9D but his hypothesis is that Trump was trying =
to follow through on a campaign promise and assuage his supporters who have=
 lost manufacturing jobs, and who may believe that tariffs will reverse mac=
roeconomic
trends and reopen factories.<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-botto=
m:0px;">In this regard, the veteran banker viewed the president=E2=80=99s m=
otivations as genuine rather than theatrical: =E2=80=9CHe thinks those peop=
le who lost those jobs, and those steel mills, should be back, because it=
=E2=80=99s unfair that the Chinese are producing steel and polluting the ai=
r and not paying people living wages, and selling steel cheaper in the Unit=
ed States than we can produce it here.=E2=80=9D Did he think it would work,=
 I asked?
=E2=80=9CProbably not,=E2=80=9D he averred. But it may not matter: Most vot=
ers are likely to remember the theater of the tariff threats, but fewer wil=
l notice when they are rolled back or postponed.=C2=A0=C2=A0</p><p style=3D=
"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><br/>Trump, the banker continued, was only co=
nsidering =E2=80=9Cthe part of the equation he wants to look at=E2=80=9D=E2=
=80=94obsessing over lost manufacturing jobs while seemingly ignoring that =
technology and service sector jobs have grown G.D.P. and lowered the unempl=
oyment rate during
the past quarter-century. Indeed, many on Wall Street privately recognize t=
hat Trump has hyperbolically oversimplified a nuanced issue. To wit: Americ=
ans who rely on Walmart for low prices would never knowingly support tariff=
s that affect our supply chain relationships with Mexico and China, likely =
passing on the higher costs to them. =E2=80=9CSo at the same time he=E2=80=
=99s trying to help them, he=E2=80=99s hurting them,=E2=80=9D the banker sa=
id. =E2=80=9CThe price of everything they=E2=80=99re going to buy is going =
to go up
dramatically=E2=80=94tomorrow. And that steel mill, if it comes back, will =
take five to 10 years to come back.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/></p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Sure, consumers could buy domestic=E2=80=A6 in theo=
ry. But there are many commodities for which there is no =E2=80=9CBuy Ameri=
can=E2=80=9D option. =E2=80=9CWe don=E2=80=99t <em>make</em> athletic shoes=
 in the United States,=E2=80=9D my smart Wall Street source explained. =E2=
=80=9CYou can buy a Nike, or you can buy an On, or you can buy a New Balanc=
e, but they=E2=80=99re all made offshore.=E2=80=9D The same goes for
cellphones, which are mostly made in China, and a million other consumer go=
ods. =E2=80=9CThat cellphone that retails for $1,500 in the United States, =
it=E2=80=99s made for $500 to $600 in China,=E2=80=9D he continued, noting =
the complexity of global supply chains and the depth of Asia=E2=80=99s manu=
facturing base. =E2=80=9CIf we needed to make that cellphone in the United =
States, it would cost over $2,000, and it would retail for $4,000.=E2=80=9D=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;"><br/>Trump not only dismisses or misunderstands =
these obstacles, he also
underestimates the resulting inflationary pressure, both from the tariffs t=
hemselves and any retaliatory actions by other countries=E2=80=94which are =
inevitable. =E2=80=9CHe does believe tariffs work, but when he sees the rea=
ction, he somehow is always surprised,=E2=80=9D the banker explained. =E2=
=80=9CHe keeps telling people that there shouldn=E2=80=99t be a reaction, b=
ut there <em>is</em> a reaction. Then he backs off=E2=80=9D and claims a co=
ncession. He told me that he suspects White House staff were working overti=
me with the Mexicans and
the Canadians to extract anything that could be spun by Trump as a quick vi=
ctory. (The White House did not respond to my request for comment.)</p></di=
v>
